tooltip.text:
A high voltage is likely indicating that the utility's incoming voltage is too high.  Consider disconnecting expensive equipment and contacting your utility.  High voltage can damage equipment or cause arcing.  

A low voltage indicates that there is likely excessive voltage drop within your facility or that the utility is providing a low voltage to your meter.  Consider wiring heavy loads separately to avoid large voltage drops within the facility.  Low voltage won't harm equipment in short term, but may cause intermittant outages, low quality output or damage equipment in the long term.

Power Factor is the ratio of Real power to Apparant power.  Your utility may charge you for having a low power factor throughout your facility.  Typically, any power factor above 80% is fine, though it is typical for motors to be between 60-80% when operating normally.  If you are experiencing a consistently low power factor you can correct it with VFD's on motors, a capacitor bank or a solar inverter (that is setup to correct the power factor using it's inverter).  Low power factors when the power is very low or off are not important and are ignored in this graph.

The frequency is set by the utility and is almost always kept well within the expected range.  A low frequency event may indicate problems on the electric grid, and are not likely caused by your facility.
